 descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of the Russo-Japanese War]]\n[[Category:People of the Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Russian people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Victims of Red Terror in Soviet Russia]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Russia]]\n[[Category:People of the 1905 Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:People executed by Russia by firing squad]]\n[[Category:Executed Russian people]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Russia]]\n[[Category:20th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Dethroned monarchs]]\n[[Category:Tsesarevichs of Russia]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "175.37.32.56", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFamily background)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_II_of_Russia"}
{"title_page": "Zap, North Dakota", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Zap, North Dakota\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \"The little town with a big heart\"\n|motto                    = \n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Zap, North Dakota.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Immanuel Lutheran Church in Zap\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = ND Mercer County Zap.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Zap, North Dakota\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[North Dakota]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in North Dakota|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Mercer County, North Dakota|Mercer]]\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         = \n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 2.72\n|area_land_km2            = 2.72\n|area_water_km2           = 0\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 1.05\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 1.05\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 231\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 237\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = MDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -6\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 563\n|elevation_ft             = 1847\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|17|14|N|101|55|26|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 58580\n|area_code                = [[Area code 701|701]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 38-88140\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1032903<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.wrtc.com/zapnd/|wrtc.com/zapnd}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Zap''' is a city in [[Mercer County, North Dakota|Mercer County]], [[North Dakota]], United States. The population was 237 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"2010 Census (City)\">{{cite web|title=2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |work=American FactFinder |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=May 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |archivedate=July 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nZap was founded in 1913 along a [[branch line]] of the [[Northern Pacific Railway]] that began in [[Mandan, North Dakota|Mandan]]. The exact origin of the name is uncertain, though there are numerous unconfirmed theories; some say the town was named after ''Zapp'', which was either a prominent Minnesota banking family or a coal-mining town in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zap History Information|url=http://www.wrtc.com/zapnd/history.htm|publisher=City of Zap|accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Wick>{{cite web|last=Wick|first=Douglas A.|title=Zap (Mercer County)|url=http://www.webfamilytree.com/North_Dakota_Place_Names/Z/zap_%28mercer_county%29.htm|work=North Dakota Place Names|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref> Zap has been noted for its [[Place names considered unusual|unusual place name]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Petras|first1=Kathryn|last2=Petras|first2=Ross|title=Unusually Stupid Americans: A Compendium of All-American Stupidity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U9kM5m3VeUAC&pg=PA246|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-41761-9|page=246}}</ref>\n\n==The \"Zip to Zap\"==\n{{Main|Zip to Zap}}\nThe town of Zap is probably most widely known for the [[Zip to Zap]] riot, which occurred on May 10, 1969. The Zip to Zap was originally intended as a spring break diversion. Between 2000 and 3000 people descended upon the town after an article by Chuck Stroup, originally appearing in the [[North Dakota State University]] ''Spectrum'' newspaper, and then later picked up by the [[Associated Press]], compelled busloads and chartered planes full of people from around the United States to go there.\n\nCOVID-19 will win. When the mayor finally exited the bar in the middle of the night and discovered a bonfire on main street and realized the size of the crowd in his tiny town, he panicked and called the governor, [[William L. Guy|William Guy]].  At dawn, marching in formation and armed with bayonets placed, the [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] invaded the town and forced the crowd to leave Zap.  The event moved to several other towns before the Governor announced that a park in [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] would host the crowd.  The then-popular rock station, KFYR, and their disc jockeys were in communication with event organizers and falsely reported where the crowd had gone before they arrived, effectively directing all the listeners on which small town and park to proceed to next.  In one village, locals cleaned out the Farmers Union of every implement handle in order to patrol their town against the wave of invading [[hippie]]s and cowboys.Also in america this village has been affected by COVID-19\n\n==Geography==\nZap is located at {{coord|47|17|14|N|101|55|26|W|type:city}} (47.287157, -101.923787).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is located in the [[prairie]] country along [[Spring Creek (North Dakota)|Spring Creek]], a tributary of the [[Knife River]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|1.05|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all of it land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220065340/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=February 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n<div style=\"width:75%\">\n{{Weather box\n|location = Zap - Beulah Field\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 19.6\n|Feb high F = 21.1\n|Mar high F = 36.5\n|Apr high F = 52.9\n|May high F = 64.6\n|Jun high F = 74.0\n|Jul high F = 83.1\n|Aug high F = 80.8\n|Sep high F = 70.5\n|Oct high F = 55.5\n|Nov high F = 44.3\n|Dec high F = 20.6\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = \u22123.7\n|Feb low F =  1.1\n|Mar low F = 14.7\n|Apr low F = 30.0\n|May low F = 37.4\n|Jun low F = 48.9\n|Jul low F = 56.1\n|Aug low F = 50.8\n|Sep low F = 41.9\n|Oct low F = 27.6\n|Nov low F = 19.9\n|Dec low F = \u22120.8\n|year low F=\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.4\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.4\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.6\n|Apr precipitation inch = 1.1\n|May precipitation inch = 2.0\n|Jun precipitation inch = 3.3\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.4\n|Aug precipitation inch = 1.8\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.5\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.4\n|year precipitation inch=15.1\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web\n|url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=56923&refer=wikipedia |title =Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Zap - Beulah Field, North Dakota\n|publisher=Weatherbase\n|year=2011\n}}\nRetrieved on November 24, 2011.\n</ref>\n|date=November 2011\n}}\n</div>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 257\n|1930= 406\n|1940= 574\n|1950= 425\n|1960= 339\n|1970= 271\n|1980= 511\n|1990= 287\n|2000= 231\n|2010= 237\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=231\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 1, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302111640/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=March 2, 2013 }}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref> of 2010, there were 237 people, 109 households, and 70 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|225.7|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 135 housing units at an average density of {{convert|128.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 91.6% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.0% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 4.2% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.4% of the population.\n\nThere were 109 households of which 24.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 8.3% had a male householder with no wife present, and 35.8% were non-families. 31.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 11% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.17 and the average family size was 2.63.\n\nThe median age in the city was 49.1 years. 17.7% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 18.2% were from 25 to 44; 38.8% were from 45 to 64; and 16% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 54.0% male and 46.0% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 231 people, 101 households, and 68 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 221.8 people per square mile (85.8/km\u00b2). There were 129 housing units at an average density of 123.8 per square mile (47.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 95.24% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.90% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 0.87% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 101 households out of which 25.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 60.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 31.7% were non-families. 29.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.29 and the average family size was 2.78.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 21.6% under the age of 18, 5.2% from 18 to 24, 25.5% from 25 to 44, 33.3% from 45 to 64, and 14.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 44 years. For every 100 females, there were 100.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $30,536, and the median income for a family was $34,063. Males had a median income of $30,625 versus $18,125 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,175. About 5.2% of families and 10.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.6% of those under the age of eighteen and 18.2% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wrtc.com/zapnd/ City of Zap official website]\n* [[North Dakota Public Radio]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222627/http://www.prairiepublic.org/programs/datebook/bydate/04/0504/051004.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> article] with details on the ''Zip to Zap''\n* Another [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204231/http://www.in-forum.com/specials/century/jan3/week9.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> article] discussing the historical importance of the ''Zip to Zap''\n* [http://www.edutech.nodak.edu/ndsta/shafer.htm Spinning the Zip to Zap: Student Journalist Responsibility and Vulnerability in the Late 1960s] by Richard Shafer\n\n{{Mercer County, North Dakota}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Mercer County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Cities in North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1913]]\n[[Category:1913 