{"title_page": "Grace Mann Brown", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Grace Mann Brown\n|image         = Grace_Mann_Brown_1901.jpg\n|caption       = \"Cordially Yours Grace M. Brown\" taken from her book \"Studies in Spiritual Harmony\"\n|birth_name    = Grace Mann\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1859|4|16}}\n|birth_place   = Pippin, Wisconsin\n|death_date    = {{death year and age|1925|1859|4}}\n|death_place   = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|resting_place = Fairmount Cemetery, Denver\n|residence     = 1645 Steele Street, Denver, Colorado\n|known_for     = [[New Thought]]'s Author\n|home_town     = Denver, Colorado\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Joseph Lyman Brown|1878|1921|end=died}}\n|children      = Bernice Brown Keen, James Leslie Brown, Eunice Brown\n|parents       = Major James Cook Mann and Mary Stem (Stears?) Mann\n|signature     = Signature_of_Grace_Mann_Brown.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Grace Mann Brown''' (April 16, 1859; Pippin, Wisconsin,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/herringshawsamer00chic \"Brown, Grace Mann\"] \u2013 Herringshaw American Blue Book of Biography (1914), p. 141</ref>{{spaced ndash}}1925; Denver, Colorado) was an American writer and spiritual leader. Her work was related to the [[New Thought|New Thought Movement]], [[Divine Science]] and [[Christian Science]]. Much of her work focused on [[spirituality]], [[metaphysics]], [[mysticism]], [[esoteric]] and [[Occult|occult sciences]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nGrace Mann Brown was the daughter of Major James Cook Mann (died October 30, 1897) and Mary Stem Mann. Brown was educated at Eden Hall in the Sacred Heart Convent in [[Torresdale, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Torresdale, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=wu.89080103955;view=image;seq=122;q1=%22Brown%2C%20Grace%20Mann%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=134 |title=Record Details Woman's who's who of America : a biographical dictionary ... 1914\u201315. (From Hathi Trust) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2012-06-10 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\nGrace Mann married Joseph Lyman Brown (1851{{spaced ndash}}November 10, 1921) from [[Denver, Colorado]], on October 20, 1878. He was an engineer at the Denver Gas and Electric Co. The couple had three children: Bernice Brown (1888\u20131937), who married a Mr. Keen; James Leslie Brown (May 10, 1891\u2013 ?), who became president of Thompson Manufacturing Co. in Denver; and Eunice Brown (1903\u20131945).\n\nBrown died in 1925 and was buried in [[Fairmount Cemetery (Denver, Colorado)|Fairmount Cemetery]] in Denver, Colorado.\n\n== Career ==\nGrace Mann Brown was active in the New Thought Movement, writing and lecturing extensively. She also wrote some of her works under the pen name '''Ione'''. She was instrumental in creating The Order of the Essenes and was its President. In 1906, Brown was Vice President of the [[List of New Thought denominations and independent centers|World New Thought Federation]].\n\nBrown would succeed Fannie B. James as Editor of ''[[Fulfillment Magazine]]''. Also, from 1920 to 1921, Brown was Bookkeeper for the [[American Unitarian Association]]. She founded the Modern Society of the Essenes: Essene Circle.\n\n== Writing ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''Studies in Spiritual Harmony'' (as Ione; Reed Publishing Company, 1901\u20131903, 134 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024531;view=image;seq=24;q1=%22by%20ione%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=18 |title=Description is given in the magazine Now. v.3 (1902\u201303) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-04-16 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226992;view=image;seq=191;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=184 |title=Description in the magazine ''Unity''. v. 16 (1902) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-09-26 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/studiesinspiritu00ione |title=Studies in spiritual harmony : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Food Studies'' (as Ione; Denver, The Reed publishing company, 1902\u20131904  101 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024533;view=image;seq=235;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=8 |title=From ''Now'' magazine, v.5 (1904\u201305) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-04-16 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Hathi Trust  Digital Library\">{{cite book|last=Brown (Ione)|first=Grace Mann|title=Food Studies|year=1902|publisher=The Reed Publishing Company|location=Denver|pages=101|hdl=2027/osu.32435016776692}}</ref> \n* ''Seven Steps in the life of S. A. Weltmer'' (Nevada, Mo.: Weltmer Institute, 1906)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/sevenstepsinlif00browgoog |title=Seven Steps in the Life of Prof. S.A. Weltmer |author=Grace (Mann) Brown |publisher=Internet Archive |date=1906, digitized 2001 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Online Book in Open Library |publisher=Openlibrary.org |date= |ol = 23498089M}}</ref>\n* ''Life Lessons: A Series of Practical Lessons of Life, from Life, and about Life'' (Hudson Press, 1906, 207 pages)\n* ''Soul Songs by Ione''  (Grace M. Brown, 1907)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/soulsongs00ione |title=Soul songs : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''The Word made Flesh, A Study in Healing.'' (Grace M. Brown, 1908)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101076520376;view=image;seq=475;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=128 |title=Ad From : Philistine: A Periodical of Protest,V.28\u201329 (1909\u201310) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-11-17 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226851;view=image;seq=89;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=67 |title=Description in ''Unity'' V. 30 (1909) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>  \n* ''To-day; the Present Moment is God's Own Time'' (Grace M. Brown, 1910\u20131911, 200 pages)<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024527;view=image;seq=208;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=42 Description of the book is given in the magazine ''Now'' V.7\u20139 (1910\u201312)] (Note: they mistakenly call it ''A Day'')</ref>\n* ''The Inner Breath; 'Vivenda Causa',  a revelation of old world wisdom in new world form.'' (Memphis, Tenn., The Business philosopher  (c. 1922) 4 p.&nbsp;1., 7\u2013182 p.&nbsp;20&nbsp;cm)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/innerbreathviven00ione |title=The inner breath; \"vivendi causa\" : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Dollars and Health: concerning the psychology of the [[spleen]] and other things...'' (Written and published by Grace M. Brown, Denver [1915?). 20 pages''\n* ''Think Right for Health and Success'' (Edward J. Clode, 1916, 184 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3038488;view=image;seq=188;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=182 |title=Description of this book is given in the mag. Theosophical Outlook V. 1\u20132 1916\u201317 |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-07-07 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/thinkrightforhea00ione |title=Think right for health and success : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Mental Harmony'' (Edward J. Clode, 1916, 195 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/mentalharmonyits00ione |title=Mental harmony : its influence on life : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles in journals and magazines ===\n[[File:Practical Metaphysics.jpg|thumb|Drawing of Grace Mann Brown in the article \"Practical Metaphysics\"]]\n\n* ''The [[Essene]]'' \u2013 monthly magazine published by Brown, 1900\u20131917<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433081679783;view=image;seq=13;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=3 Ad in Business woman's mag.], Hathi Trust website</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://209.68.57.225/rare_books/essene-book/essene-antique-intro.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121209105043/http://209.68.57.225/rare_books/essene-book/essene-antique-intro.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-09 |title=Volume VI, number 1 |publisher=209.68.57.225 |accessdate=2013-02-17 }}</ref>\n* ''Fulfillment'' \u2013 monthly metaphysical magazine 1904\u20131907, later became the ''Weltmer Magazine''<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oellC3zzD2cC&q=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+%22Fulfillment%22&dq=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+%22Fulfillment%22 |title=Description is given in the mag. Unity, Volume 24 (1916) |via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2013-02-17|year=1906 }}</ref><ref>Unity V.25</ref>\n* \"Practical Metaphysics\" in ''The Herald of the Golden Age'' Vol. 10, No. 4 Oct 1905 p.69<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/heraldofgoldenoct1905exetuoft |title=Herald of the Golden Age : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date= |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* \"The Greatest Thing\" in ''Master Mind Magazine'' Vol. 3 of 15 Oct 1912 to March 1913 p. 153<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WiCY9xNoE_UC&pg=PR207&dq=%22master+mind%22+%22the+greatest+thing%22+%22grace+m.+brown#v=onepage&q=%22master%20mind%22%20%22the%20greatest%20thing%22%20%22grace%20m.%20brown&f=false |title=Master Mind Magazine, October 1912 to March 1913 - Annie Rix Militz - Google Books |via=[[Google Books]]|date= January 2003|accessdate=2013-02-17|isbn=9780766134744 |last1=Militz |first1=Annie Rix }}</ref>\n* ''Washington News Letter'' several appearances.<ref>{{cite document|title=''Washington News Letter'' V.23 Oct 1917\u201318 p. 62 |date=2010-10-02 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081642047}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=\"Realisation\" in ''Washington news letter''. v. 17 (1911\u201312) p 680 |date=2010-10-02 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081641981}}</ref><ref>[http://hdl.handle.net/2027/nyp.33433081641932?urlappend=%3Bseq=352 ''Washington news letter''. v. 11 (October 1905 \u2013 September 1906) p. 334] \u2013 reprint from ''Fulfillment''</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=''Washington news letter''. v. 11 (October 1905 \u2013 September 1906). p.552 |date=2010-09-23 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081641932}}</ref>\n* ''Now'' magazine, several appearances.<ref>{{cite document|title=''Now''. v.17\u201318 (1920\u201321) p.341 |date=2011-05-05 |hdl = 2027/uc1.b4024535}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=''Now''. v.17\u201318 (1920\u201321) p 367 |date=2011-05-05 |hdl = 2027/uc1.b4024535}}</ref>\n* ''The Modern World'' volume 9, page 128<ref>{{cite document|title=The Modern world. v. 9 (Apr. - Nov. 1908). - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |date=2010-10-22 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081679825}}</ref>\n* ''Mind Magazine'' volume 8, number 3, June 1901, p. 149<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/mind01unkngoog#page/n173/mode/2up/search/149 |title=Mind : science, philosophy, religion, psychology, metaphysics, occultism |date= |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''The Balance'' from The Balance Publishing Co. Denver, Colo. A magazine of learning, of a standard 64p. monthly.\n\n== Lectures ==\nBrown spoke at the Fifth Annual Convention of the New Thought Federation. The convention was held in [[Nevada, Missouri]], on September 26\u201329, 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226927;view=image;seq=247;q1=%22grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=239 |title=From the mag. Unity. v. 23 (1905) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref> She also gave a lecture entitled \"Treasures\" at the Unity Building Dedication Convention on Sunday August 19, 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226901;view=image;seq=110;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=104 |title=From Unity V. 25 pp. 104\u2013105 |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian Science]]\n* [[Church of Divine Science]]\n* [[New Thought]]\n* [[Unitarianism]]\n* [[Sidney Abram Weltmer]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== References ==\n* [[s:Page:Woman's who's who of America, 1914-15.djvu/122|Who is Who in America 1914-1915]]\n* [https://archive.org/details/herringshawsamer00chic Herringshaw's American Blue Book of Biography] (Thomas William Herringsaw, 1914)\n* ''Catalog of Copyright entries from 1900 to 1917''\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=cxiBw0BWq-MC&pg=PA176-IA2&lpg=PA176-IA2&dq=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+Essenes&source=bl&ots=kcVwvy2GD_&sig=03XYhjpDeVLeCsoEquZUg8ieObk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aLn5T_fAGcrc0QG-joXbBg&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22Grace%20M.%20brown%22%20Essenes&f=false Referenced in ''Master Mind'' Magazines 1913-1914]\n* [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?q1=%22Grace+M.+Brown%22&lmt=ft&a=srchls Other references can be found in the HATIHI TRUST Digital Library]\n* [http://digital.denverlibrary.org/cdm/genealogy/#nat Denver Public Library Digital Collection, History, Genealogy, Ob, Cem,...]\n\n===Further reading===\n* ''The Good Health Journal'', November Number (1908) ed. J.H. Kellogg M.D.\n* [http://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015074774624?urlappend=%3Bseq=26 \"The Essene Brotherhood, Vegetarian\"] in ''The Vegetarian Magazine'' (v.11 no.11 1909) relates information on The Essene Brotherhood of which Brown was a founder and leader.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://cdm16079.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15330coll22/id/38943/rec/4 First Christian Science Church from Denver Public Library]\n* [http://cdm16079.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15330coll22/id/38999/rec/3 Divine Science Church from the Denver Public Library]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=brown&GSfn=grace+&GSmn=mann&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSob=n&GRid=35460402&df=all& |title=The Grave Stone of Grace Mann Brown|publisher=Findagrave.com }}\n* [http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Brown&GSiman=1&GSsr=281&GScid=57267&GRid=35460405& Joseph Lyman Brown], Find a Grave Website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Grace Mann}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Occultists]]\n[[Category:New Thought writers]]\n[[Category:American Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Unity Church]]\n[[Category:New Thought mystics]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Grace Mann Brown\n|image         = Grace_Mann_Brown_1901.jpg\n|caption       = \"Cordially Yours Grace M. Brown\" taken from her book \"Studies in Spiritual Harmony\"\n|birth_name    = Grace Mann\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1859|4|16}}\n|birth_place   = Pippin, Wisconsin\n|death_date    = {{death year and age|1925|1859|4}}\n|death_place   = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|resting_place = Fairmount Cemetery, Denver\n|residence     = 1645 Steele Street, Denver, Colorado\n|known_for     = [[New Thought]]'s Author\n|home_town     = Denver, Colorado\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Joseph Lyman Brown|1878|1921|end=died}}\n|children      = Bernice Brown Keen, James Leslie Brown, Eunice Brown\n|parents       = Major James Cook Mann and Mary Stem (Stears?) Mann\n|signature     = Signature_of_Grace_Mann_Brown.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Grace Mann Brown''' (April 16, 1859; Pippin, Wisconsin,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/herringshawsamer00chic \"Brown, Grace Mann\"] \u2013 Herringshaw American Blue Book of Biography (1914), p. 141</ref>{{spaced ndash}}1925; Denver, Colorado) was an American writer and spiritual leader. Her work was related to the [[New Thought|New Thought Movement]], [[Divine Science]] and [[Christian Science]]. Much of her work focused on [[spirituality]], [[metaphysics]], [[mysticism]], [[esoteric]] and [[Occult|occult sciences]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nGrace Mann Brown was the daughter of Major James Cook Mann (died October 30, 1897) and Mary Stem Mann. Brown was educated at Eden Hall in the Sacred Heart Convent in [[Torresdale, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Torresdale, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=wu.89080103955;view=image;seq=122;q1=%22Brown%2C%20Grace%20Mann%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=134 |title=Record Details Woman's who's who of America : a biographical dictionary ... 1914\u201315. (From Hathi Trust) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2012-06-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\nGrace Mann married Joseph Lyman Brown (1851{{spaced ndash}}November 10, 1921) from [[Denver, Colorado]], on October 20, 1878. He was an engineer at the Denver Gas and Electric Co. The couple had three children: Bernice Brown (1888\u20131937), who married a Mr. Keene; James Leslie Brown (May 10, 1891\u2013 ?), who became president of Thompson Manufacturing Co. in Denver; and Eunice Brown (1903\u20131945).\n\nBrown died in 1925 and was buried in [[Fairmount Cemetery (Denver, Colorado)|Fairmount Cemetery]] in Denver, Colorado.\n\n== Career ==\nGrace Mann Brown was active in the New Thought Movement, writing and lecturing extensively. She also wrote some of her works under the pen name '''Ione'''. She was instrumental in creating The Order of the Essenes and was its President. In 1906, Brown was Vice President of the [[List of New Thought denominations and independent centers|World New Thought Federation]].\n\nBrown would succeed Fannie B. James as Editor of ''[[Fulfillment Magazine]]''. Also, from 1920 to 1921, Brown was Bookkeeper for the [[American Unitarian Association]]. She founded the Modern Society of the Essenes: Essene Circle.\n\n== Writing ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''Studies in Spiritual Harmony'' (as Ione; Reed Publishing Company, 1901\u20131903, 134 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024531;view=image;seq=24;q1=%22by%20ione%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=18 |title=Description is given in the magazine Now. v.3 (1902\u201303) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-04-16 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226992;view=image;seq=191;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=184 |title=Description in the magazine ''Unity''. v. 16 (1902) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-09-26 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/studiesinspiritu00ione |title=Studies in spiritual harmony : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Food Studies'' (as Ione; Denver, The Reed publishing company, 1902\u20131904  101 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024533;view=image;seq=235;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=8 |title=From ''Now'' magazine, v.5 (1904\u201305) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-04-16 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Hathi Trust  Digital Library\">{{cite book|last=Brown (Ione)|first=Grace Mann|title=Food Studies|year=1902|publisher=The Reed Publishing Company|location=Denver|pages=101|hdl=2027/osu.32435016776692}}</ref> \n* ''Seven Steps in the life of S. A. Weltmer'' (Nevada, Mo.: Weltmer Institute, 1906)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/sevenstepsinlif00browgoog |title=Seven Steps in the Life of Prof. S.A. Weltmer |author=Grace (Mann) Brown |publisher=Internet Archive |date=1906, digitized 2001 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Online Book in Open Library |publisher=Openlibrary.org |date= |ol = 23498089M}}</ref>\n* ''Life Lessons: A Series of Practical Lessons of Life, from Life, and about Life'' (Hudson Press, 1906, 207 pages)\n* ''Soul Songs by Ione''  (Grace M. Brown, 1907)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/soulsongs00ione |title=Soul songs : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |access-date=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''The Word made Flesh, A Study in Healing.'' (Grace M. Brown, 1908)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101076520376;view=image;seq=475;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=128 |title=Ad From : Philistine: A Periodical of Protest,V.28\u201329 (1909\u201310) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-11-17 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226851;view=image;seq=89;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=67 |title=Description in ''Unity'' V. 30 (1909) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>  \n* ''To-day; the Present Moment is God's Own Time'' (Grace M. Brown, 1910\u20131911, 200 pages)<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4024527;view=image;seq=208;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=42 Description of the book is given in the magazine ''Now'' V.7\u20139 (1910\u201312)] (Note: they mistakenly call it ''A Day'')</ref>\n* ''The Inner Breath; 'Vivenda Causa',  a revelation of old world wisdom in new world form.'' (Memphis, Tenn., The Business philosopher  (c. 1922) 4 p.&nbsp;1., 7\u2013182 p.&nbsp;20&nbsp;cm)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/innerbreathviven00ione |title=The inner breath; \"vivendi causa\" : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Dollars and Health: concerning the psychology of the [[spleen]] and other things...'' (Written and published by Grace M. Brown, Denver [1915?). 20 pages''\n* ''Think Right for Health and Success'' (Edward J. Clode, 1916, 184 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3038488;view=image;seq=188;q1=%22by%20grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=182 |title=Description of this book is given in the mag. Theosophical Outlook V. 1\u20132 1916\u201317 |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2011-07-07 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/thinkrightforhea00ione |title=Think right for health and success : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''Mental Harmony'' (Edward J. Clode, 1916, 195 pages)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/mentalharmonyits00ione |title=Mental harmony : its influence on life : Ione, b. 1859 : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date=2001-03-10 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles in journals and magazines ===\n[[File:Practical Metaphysics.jpg|thumb|Drawing of Grace Mann Brown in the article \"Practical Metaphysics\"]]\n\n* ''The [[Essene]]'' \u2013 monthly magazine published by Brown, 1900\u20131917<ref>[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433081679783;view=image;seq=13;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=3 Ad in Business woman's mag.], Hathi Trust website</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://209.68.57.225/rare_books/essene-book/essene-antique-intro.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121209105043/http://209.68.57.225/rare_books/essene-book/essene-antique-intro.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-09 |title=Volume VI, number 1 |publisher=209.68.57.225 |accessdate=2013-02-17 }}</ref>\n* ''Fulfillment'' \u2013 monthly metaphysical magazine 1904\u20131907, later became the ''Weltmer Magazine''<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oellC3zzD2cC&q=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+%22Fulfillment%22&dq=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+%22Fulfillment%22 |title=Description is given in the mag. Unity, Volume 24 (1916) |via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2013-02-17|year=1906 }}</ref><ref>Unity V.25</ref>\n* \"Practical Metaphysics\" in ''The Herald of the Golden Age'' Vol. 10, No. 4 Oct 1905 p.69<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/heraldofgoldenoct1905exetuoft |title=Herald of the Golden Age : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |date= |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* \"The Greatest Thing\" in ''Master Mind Magazine'' Vol. 3 of 15 Oct 1912 to March 1913 p. 153<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WiCY9xNoE_UC&pg=PR207&dq=%22master+mind%22+%22the+greatest+thing%22+%22grace+m.+brown#v=onepage&q=%22master%20mind%22%20%22the%20greatest%20thing%22%20%22grace%20m.%20brown&f=false |title=Master Mind Magazine, October 1912 to March 1913 - Annie Rix Militz - Google Books |via=[[Google Books]]|date= January 2003|accessdate=2013-02-17|isbn=9780766134744 |last1=Militz |first1=Annie Rix }}</ref>\n* ''Washington News Letter'' several appearances.<ref>{{cite document|title=''Washington News Letter'' V.23 Oct 1917\u201318 p. 62 |date=2010-10-02 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081642047}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=\"Realisation\" in ''Washington news letter''. v. 17 (1911\u201312) p 680 |date=2010-10-02 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081641981}}</ref><ref>[http://hdl.handle.net/2027/nyp.33433081641932?urlappend=%3Bseq=352 ''Washington news letter''. v. 11 (October 1905 \u2013 September 1906) p. 334] \u2013 reprint from ''Fulfillment''</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=''Washington news letter''. v. 11 (October 1905 \u2013 September 1906). p.552 |date=2010-09-23 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081641932}}</ref>\n* ''Now'' magazine, several appearances.<ref>{{cite document|title=''Now''. v.17\u201318 (1920\u201321) p.341 |date=2011-05-05 |hdl = 2027/uc1.b4024535}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=''Now''. v.17\u201318 (1920\u201321) p 367 |date=2011-05-05 |hdl = 2027/uc1.b4024535}}</ref>\n* ''The Modern World'' volume 9, page 128<ref>{{cite document|title=The Modern world. v. 9 (Apr. - Nov. 1908). - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |date=2010-10-22 |hdl = 2027/nyp.33433081679825}}</ref>\n* ''Mind Magazine'' volume 8, number 3, June 1901, p. 149<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/mind01unkngoog#page/n173/mode/2up/search/149 |title=Mind : science, philosophy, religion, psychology, metaphysics, occultism |date= |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n* ''The Balance'' from The Balance Publishing Co. Denver, Colo. A magazine of learning, of a standard 64p. monthly.\n\n== Lectures ==\nBrown spoke at the Fifth Annual Convention of the New Thought Federation. The convention was held in [[Nevada, Missouri]], on September 26\u201329, 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226927;view=image;seq=247;q1=%22grace%20m.%20brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=239 |title=From the mag. Unity. v. 23 (1905) |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref> She also gave a lecture entitled \"Treasures\" at the Unity Building Dedication Convention on Sunday August 19, 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070226901;view=image;seq=110;q1=%22Grace%20M.%20Brown%22;start=1;size=10;page=search;num=104 |title=From Unity V. 25 pp. 104\u2013105 |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian Science]]\n* [[Church of Divine Science]]\n* [[New Thought]]\n* [[Unitarianism]]\n* [[Sidney Abram Weltmer]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== References ==\n* [[s:Page:Woman's who's who of America, 1914-15.djvu/122|Who is Who in America 1914-1915]]\n* [https://archive.org/details/herringshawsamer00chic Herringshaw's American Blue Book of Biography] (Thomas William Herringsaw, 1914)\n* ''Catalog of Copyright entries from 1900 to 1917''\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=cxiBw0BWq-MC&pg=PA176-IA2&lpg=PA176-IA2&dq=%22Grace+M.+brown%22+Essenes&source=bl&ots=kcVwvy2GD_&sig=03XYhjpDeVLeCsoEquZUg8ieObk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aLn5T_fAGcrc0QG-joXbBg&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22Grace%20M.%20brown%22%20Essenes&f=false Referenced in ''Master Mind'' Magazines 1913-1914]\n* [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?q1=%22Grace+M.+Brown%22&lmt=ft&a=srchls Other references can be found in the HATIHI TRUST Digital Library]\n* [http://digital.denverlibrary.org/cdm/genealogy/#nat Denver Public Library Digital Collection, History, Genealogy, Ob, Cem,...]\n\n===Further reading===\n* ''The Good Health Journal'', November Number (1908) ed. J.H. Kellogg M.D.\n* [http://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015074774624?urlappend=%3Bseq=26 \"The Essene Brotherhood, Vegetarian\"] in ''The Vegetarian Magazine'' (v.11 no.11 1909) relates information on The Essene Brotherhood of which Brown was a founder and leader.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://cdm16079.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15330coll22/id/38943/rec/4 First Christian Science Church from Denver Public Library]\n* [http://cdm16079.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15330coll22/id/38999/rec/3 Divine Science Church from the Denver Public Library]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=brown&GSfn=grace+&GSmn=mann&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSob=n&GRid=35460402&df=all& |title=The Grave Stone of Grace Mann Brown|publisher=Findagrave.com }}\n* [http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Brown&GSiman=1&GSsr=281&GScid=57267&GRid=35460405& Joseph Lyman Brown], Find a Grave Website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Grace Mann}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Occultists]]\n[[Category:New Thought writers]]\n[[Category:American Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Unity Church]]\n[[Category:New Thought mystics]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n", "name_user": "Parkwells", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grace_Mann_Brown"}
{"title_page": "Angela Brooks", "text_new": "{{for|the biologist and geneticist|Angela N. Brooks}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Angela Brooks\n| image                 = Angela Brooks, FAIA.jpg\n| image_size            = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Angela Brooks\n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} (if dead)\n                               {{Birth date and age|yyyy|mm|dd}} (known date)\n                               {{Birth year and age|yyyy|mm}} (known month)\n                               {{Birth year and age|yyyy}} (known year) \n                               For living people supply '''only''' the year \n                               unless the exact date is already WIDELY  \n                               published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. -->\n| birth_place           = \n| death_date            = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}}\n                               (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place           = \n| nationality           = \n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = [[Lawrence Scarpa]] \n| awards                = \n| practice              = [[Brooks + Scarpa]]\n| significant_buildings = [[Solar umbrella house]]\n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               =  {{URL|http://brooksscarpa.com}}\n}}\n'''Angela Brooks''' FAIA is an American architect based in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/office/brooks-scarpa-architects|title=Brooks + Scarpa, Witold Rybczynski Win Cooper-Hewitt National Design Award|last=Rosenfield|first=Karissa|date=May 1, 2014|newspaper=ArchDaily}}</ref> She is the Co-Principal of the [[Los Angeles]]-based architecture firm, [[Brooks + Scarpa]]. She co-founded and served as President of Livable Places,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://livableplaces.org/ |title=Livable Places |access-date=3 March 2017}}</ref> a nonprofit development company created to stimulate neighborhood revitalization in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n== Significant works ==\nBrooks was the project architect for [[Pugh + Scarpa]]'s project [[Colorado Court Housing|Colorado Court]] in Santa Monica,<ref name=\"stepup\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-stepup25-2009apr25-story.html|title=Santa Monica homeless apartment complex offers hope|last=Thornburg|first=Barbara|date=April 25, 2009|work=|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref> which was the first multi-family housing project in the USA to be [[LEED certified]]. It has 46 units. It is the first large residential complex in the United States to combine advanced sustainability with low-income housing.<ref name=\"stepup\" /><ref name=\"green\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/style/la-hm-chexcerpt30jun30-story.html|title=Green, with a high gloss|last=Stang|first=Alana|date=June 30, 2006|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Stang|first1=Alanna|last2=Hawthorne|first2=Christopher|title=The Green House: New Directions in Sustainable Architecture|date=2005|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984810|page=31|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=s_8p0usEMDgC&pg=PA31|accessdate=27 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/aug/03/realestate/re-green3|title=Green project wins on its own terms|last=Price-Robinson|first=Kathy|date=August 3, 2003|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=newsweek>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/how-design-healthier-planet-95503|title=How to Design a Healthier Planet|last=Adler|first=Jerry|date=March 4, 2007|newspaper=Newsweek}}</ref> In continuing her commitment to socially progressive design, the program was designed for homeless residents with chronic mental illness as a gathering spot to create a sense of community.<ref name=\"stepup\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nBrooks was a 2009 National AIA Young Architects Award recipient, having made an \"exceptional\" contribution to architecture early in her career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.residentialarchitect.com/culture/aia-honors-young-architects_o |title=AIA honors young architects |work=Residential Architect |date=February 3, 2009 |accessdate=2017-08-26 }}</ref> She is a [[Fellow of the American Institute of Architects]]. Brooks was also the 2010 honoree of the \u201cCharacter Approved\u201d Award by USA Network for her \u201cunparalleled ability to marry aesthetics, affordability and [[sustainability]] in the built environment\u201d, [[USA Network]] officials said.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=USA Network Announces Second Annual Character Approved Awards Celebrating Cultural Influencers and Trailblazers|date=5 February 2010|publisher=USA Network|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/usa-network-announces-second-annual-character-approved-awards-celebrating-cultural-influencers-and-trailblazers-83640257.html}}</ref> \"As buildings are among the chief contributors to energy consumption and landfill waste, the role and the voice of the architect in the future of our planet is a vital one. I hope that this feature will help me raise awareness of the issues of sustainability that have been the main objects of my career.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://argonautnews.com/venice-architect-angela-brooks-honored-with-character-approved-award-by-usa-network/|title=Venice architect Angela Brooks honored with \u2018Character Approved\u2019 award by USA Network|last=Goldman|first=Betsy|date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Brooks was a recipient 2010 American Institute of Architects Firm Award.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nBrooks + Scarpa was the winner of the 2014 [[Smithsonian Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum]] Award in Architecture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cooperhewitt.org/national-design-awards/2014-national-design-award-winners/|title=2014 National Design Award Winners {{!}} Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|date=2014-05-15|work=Cooper Hewitt Smithsonian Design Museum|access-date=2017-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBrooks was featured in the book Woman in Green: Voices of Sustainable Design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladesignfestival.org/2019-speakers-bio/angela-brooks|title=Angela Brooks, FAIA|website=LA Design Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nBrooks and Scarpa won 2019 Marvin Hall of Fame.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nBrooks is married to the American architect [[Lawrence Scarpa]], partner in Brooks + Scarpa. Brooks met Scarpa at the University of Florida.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.builderonline.com/design/awards/2019-marvin-hall-of-fame-angela-brooks-lawrence-scarpa_o|title=2019 Marvin Hall of Fame: Angela Brooks & Lawrence Scarpa|website=builderonline.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooks, Angela}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Architects from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:American women architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century American architects]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the biologist and geneticist|Angela N. Brooks}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Angela Brooks\n| image                 = Angela Brooks, FAIA.jpg\n| image_size            = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Angela Brooks\n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} (if dead)\n                               {{Birth date and age|yyyy|mm|dd}} (known date)\n                               {{Birth year and age|yyyy|mm}} (known month)\n                               {{Birth year and age|yyyy}} (known year) \n                               For living people supply '''only''' the year \n                               unless the exact date is already WIDELY  \n                               published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. -->\n| birth_place           = \n| death_date            = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}}\n                               (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place           = \n| nationality           = \n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = [[Lawrence Scarpa]] \n| awards                = \n| practice              = [[Brooks + Scarpa]]\n| significant_buildings = [[Solar umbrella house]]\n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               =  {{URL|http://brooksscarpa.com}}\n}}\n'''Angela Brooks''' FAIA is an American architect based in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/office/brooks-scarpa-architects|title=Brooks + Scarpa, Witold Rybczynski Win Cooper-Hewitt National Design Award|last=Rosenfield|first=Karissa|date=May 1, 2014|newspaper=ArchDaily}}</ref> She is the Co-Principal of the [[Los Angeles]]-based architecture firm, [[Brooks + Scarpa]]. She co-founded and served as President of Livable Places,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://livableplaces.org/ |title=Livable Places |access-date=3 March 2017}}</ref> a nonprofit development company created to stimulate neighborhood revitalization in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n== Significant works ==\nBrooks was the project architect for [[Pugh + Scarpa]]'s project [[Colorado Court Housing|Colorado Court]] in Santa Monica,<ref name=\"stepup\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-stepup25-2009apr25-story.html|title=Santa Monica homeless apartment complex offers hope|last=Thornburg|first=Barbara|date=April 25, 2009|work=|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref> which was the first multi-family housing project in the USA to be [[LEED certified]]. It has 46 units. It is the first large residential complex in the United States to combine advanced sustainability with low-income housing.<ref name=\"stepup\" /><ref name=\"green\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/style/la-hm-chexcerpt30jun30-story.html|title=Green, with a high gloss|last=Stang|first=Alana|date=June 30, 2006|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Stang|first1=Alanna|last2=Hawthorne|first2=Christopher|title=The Green House: New Directions in Sustainable Architecture|date=2005|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984810|page=31|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=s_8p0usEMDgC&pg=PA31|accessdate=27 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/aug/03/realestate/re-green3|title=Green project wins on its own terms|last=Price-Robinson|first=Kathy|date=August 3, 2003|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=newsweek>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/how-design-healthier-planet-95503|title=How to Design a Healthier Planet|last=Adler|first=Jerry|date=March 4, 2007|newspaper=Newsweek}}</ref> In continuing her commitment to socially progressive design, the program was designed for homeless residents with chronic mental illness as a gathering spot to create a sense of community.<ref name=\"stepup\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nBrooks was a 2009 National AIA Young Architects Award recipient, having made an \"exceptional\" contribution to architecture early in her career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.residentialarchitect.com/culture/aia-honors-young-architects_o |title=AIA honors young architects |work=Residential Architect |date=February 3, 2009 |accessdate=2017-08-26 }}</ref> She is a [[Fellow of the American Institute of Architects]]. Brooks was also the 2010 honoree of the \u201cCharacter Approved\u201d Award by USA Network for her \u201cunparalleled ability to marry aesthetics, affordability and [[sustainability]] in the built environment\u201d, [[USA Network]] officials said.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=USA Network Announces Second Annual Character Approved Awards Celebrating Cultural Influencers and Trailblazers|date=5 February 2010|publisher=USA Network|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/usa-network-announces-second-annual-character-approved-awards-celebrating-cultural-influencers-and-trailblazers-83640257.html}}</ref> \"As buildings are among the chief contributors to energy consumption and landfill waste, the role and the voice of the architect in the future of our planet is a vital one. I hope that this feature will help me raise awareness of the issues of sustainability that have been the main objects of my career.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://argonautnews.com/venice-architect-angela-brooks-honored-with-character-approved-award-by-usa-network/|title=Venice architect Angela Brooks honored with \u2018Character Approved\u2019 award by USA Network|last=Goldman|first=Betsy|date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Brooks was a recipient 2010 American Institute of Architects Firm Award.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBrooks + Scarpa was the winner of the 2014 [[Smithsonian Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum]] Award in Architecture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cooperhewitt.org/national-design-awards/2014-national-design-award-winners/|title=2014 National Design Award Winners {{!}} Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|date=2014-05-15|work=Cooper Hewitt Smithsonian Design Museum|access-date=2017-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBrooks was featured in the book Woman in Green: Voices of Sustainable Design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladesignfestival.org/2019-speakers-bio/angela-brooks|title=Angela Brooks, FAIA|website=LA Design Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nBrooks and Scarpa won 2019 Marvin Hall of Fame.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Personal life==\nBrooks is married to the American architect [[Lawrence Scarpa]], partner in Brooks + Scarpa. Brooks met Scarpa at the University of Florida.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.builderonline.com/design/awards/2019-marvin-hall-of-fame-angela-brooks-lawrence-scarpa_o|title=https://www.builderonline.com/design/awards/2019-marvin-hall-of-fame-angela-brooks-lawrence-scarpa_o|website=www.builderonline.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooks, Angela}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Architects from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:American women architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century American architects]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Brooks"}
{"title_page": "Gillian Duffy", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n{{this|the editor|the Labour Party member connected to \"Bigotgate\"|2010 United Kingdom general election#Bigotgate}}\n\n'''Gillian Duffy''' is an English food writer and editor of [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]], and 2015 winner of the [[James Beard Foundation]] award for Food Journalism - Visual Storytelling. She was born in [[Salisbury, England]] and having lived in [[Weston, Connecticut]]<ref name=star/> for some years, now lives in [[Provence]] and commutes regularly to New York.\nBrought up on a [[Sussex]] farm, she spent summers in France, and is fluent in French. After Finishing School (The Triangle) in London, she worked in various ad agencies \"learning the trade\".\n\nShe became art buyer for the advertising agency [[Papert Koenig Lois]], and later director of art studio Baird Harris.<ref name=star>{{citation |url=http://www.starchefs.com/GDuffy/bio.html |journal=Starchefs |title=Gillian Duffy |year=1998}}</ref>  She married Captain David Duffy, who served in the Honourable Artillery Company, later [[Royal Artillery]], in Germany and travelled extensively to France, Italy, Austria and Denmark. After spending a year in Spain and back in England, she moved with him to the United States in 1978.<ref name=star/> \n\nShe joined ''New York'' magazine in 1980 and first covered restaurants and nightlife in the magazine's ''Cue'' section.<ref name=star/> She is now the magazine's culinary editor, and founded and still organizes the \"New York Taste\" show, as well as \"New York Culinary Experience\". She appears regularly on television and radio.  She has written for other periodicals such as ''[[Marie Claire]]'' and \"Departures\" and has written two books: ''Hors d'Oeuvres, Simple, Stylish, Seasonal'' and ''New York Cooks''.  She is a supporter of the charity [[City Harvest (United States)|City Harvest]]. Her favourite restaurant in 2009 was [[Le Bernardin]]. In 2015 she was nominated for a James Beard Award for food journalism. Subsequently, she was given the James Beard Award for \"Visual Story Telling\" in April 2015.<ref name=pop>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/louise-mccready/gillian-duffy-on-the-expa_b_341175.html |author=Louise McCready |journal=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 31, 2009 |title=Gillian Duffy on the Expanding Populist Food World and How Neighborhood Joints Will Benefit from the Recession}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duffy, Gillian}}\n[[Category:English editors]]\n[[Category:English food writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Weston, Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n{{this|the editor|the Labour Party member connected to \"Bigotgate\"|2010 United Kingdom general election#Bigotgate}}\n\n'''Gillian Duffy''' is an English food writer and editor of [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]], and 2015 winner of the [[James Beard Foundation]] award for Food Journalism - Visual Storytelling. She was born in [[Salisbury, England]] and having lived in [[Weston, Connecticut]]<ref name=star/> for some years, now lives in [[Provence]] and commutes regularly to New York.\nBrought up on a [[Sussex]] farm, she spent summers in France, and is fluent in French. After Finishing School (The Triangle) in London, she worked in various ad agencies \"learning the trade\".\n\nShe became art buyer for the advertising agency [[Papert Koenig Lois]], and later director of art studio Baird Harris.<ref name=star>{{citation |url=http://www.starchefs.com/GDuffy/bio.html |journal=Starchefs |title=Gillian Duffy |year=1998}}</ref>  She married Captain David Duffy, who served in the Honourable Artillery Company, later [[Royal Artillery]], in Germany and travelled extensively to France, Italy, Austria and Denmark. After spending a year in Spain and back in England, she moved with him to the United States in 1978.<ref name=star/> \n\nShe joined ''New York'' magazine in 1980 and first covered restaurants and nightlife in the magazine's ''Cue'' section.<ref name=star/> She is now the magazine's culinary editor, and founded and still organizes the \"New York Taste\" show, as well as \"New York Culinary Experience\". She appears regularly on television and radio.  She has written for other periodicals such as ''[[Marie Claire]]'' and \"Departures\" and has written two books: ''Hors d'Oeuvres, Simple, Stylish, Seasonal'' and ''New York Cooks''.  She is a supporter of the charity [[City Harvest (organization)|City Harvest]]. Her favourite restaurant in 2009 was [[Le Bernardin]]. In 2015 she was nominated for a James Beard Award for food journalism. Subsequently, she was given the James Beard Award for \"Visual Story Telling\" in April 2015.<ref name=pop>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/louise-mccready/gillian-duffy-on-the-expa_b_341175.html |author=Louise McCready |journal=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 31, 2009 |title=Gillian Duffy on the Expanding Populist Food World and How Neighborhood Joints Will Benefit from the Recession}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duffy, Gillian}}\n[[Category:English editors]]\n[[Category:English food writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Weston, Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCity Harvest(link changed toCity Harvest (United States)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gillian_Duffy"}
{"title_page": "HSwMS Tre Kronor", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:HMS Tre Kronor.jpg|300px|HSwMS Tre Kronor]]\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[Sweden]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Sweden|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tre Kronor''\n|Ship namesake=[[Three Crowns|Tre Kronor]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[G\u00f6taverken]], Gothenburg\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=27 September 1943\n|Ship launched=16 December 1944\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=25 October 1947\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=1 January 1964\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=*''F\u00f6r Sveriges frihet''\n*(\"For the freedom of Sweden\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=[[Image:Coat of arms of Sweden.svg|100px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Tre Kronor|cruiser}}\n|Ship displacement={{Convert|7400|LT|t|0}} \n|Ship length= {{Convert|181.96|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam= {{Convert|16.45|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= \n|Ship draft={{Convert|5.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=2 shafts, 90000shp\n|Ship speed= {{Convert|33|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=618\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*''As built'' :\n*7 \u00d7 [[Bofors 152 mm gun]]s\n*20 \u00d7 [[Bofors 40 mm gun]]s\n*9 \u00d7 20 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 torpedo tubes\n*''From 1950'' :\n*7 \u00d7 {{Convert|152|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} guns\n*21 \u00d7 40 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 20 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 torpedo tubes\n|Ship armor=*{{Convert|70|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n*Deck: {{Convert|30|+|30|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n*Conning tower and turrets: {{Convert|127|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} \n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HSwMS ''Tre Kronor''''' was a [[cruiser]] of the [[Royal Swedish Navy]] built during the [[Second World War]]. \n\n== History ==\nAt the start of the war most of the ships of the Royal Swedish Navy were quite old and the navy was in need of new ships. In 1940 the government decided that three [[cruiser]]s were to be built. A political debate broke out about the cruisers and works did not start until 1943.  The ship was to be built in [[G\u00f6taverken]] in [[Gothenburg]]. Eventually only two of the cruisers were built, and the third cruiser-squadron of the [[Coastal Fleet]] would be led by the modernised AA-cruiser {{HSwMS|Gotland|1933|6}}.\n\nThe turrets used on HSwMS ''Tre Kronor'' were built by [[Bofors]] and were originally ordered by the [[Royal Netherlands Navy|Dutch Navy]] to be fitted on the two \"[[De Zeven Provinci\u00ebn-class cruiser]]s\", but after the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[German occupation of the Netherlands (Reichskommissariat)|occupation of the Netherlands]] the [[Sweden|Swedish]] government was afraid they would be claimed by the Germans so they were confiscated.\n\n''Tre Kronor'' was launched 16 December 1944, commissioned on 25 October 1947, and served until 1 January 1964.\n\n==Captains==\n*1947\u20131948: [[Erik af Klint (1901\u20131981)|Erik af Klint]]\n*1949\u20131951: Erik Friberg\n*1954\u20131954: [[Harry Bong]]\n*1954\u20131955: Magnus Starck\n*1955\u20131956: [[\u00c5ke Lindemalm]]\n*1956\u20131957: Magnus Hammar\n*1957\u20131958: Anders Nilson\n\n== References ==\n\n\n{{Tre Kronor class cruiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tre Kronor}}\n\n[[Category:Tre Kronor-class cruisers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Gothenburg]]\n[[Category:1944 ships]]\n\n\n[[it:Almirante Latorre (CL-04)#Origini]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:HMS Tre Kronor.jpg|300px|HSwMS Tre Kronor]]\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[Sweden]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Sweden|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tre Kronor''\n|Ship namesake=[[Three Crowns|Tre Kronor]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[G\u00f6taverken]], Gothenburg\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=27 September 1943\n|Ship launched=16 December 1944\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=25 October 1947\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=1 January 1964\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=*''F\u00f6r Sveriges frihet''\n*(\"For the freedom of Sweden\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=[[Image:Coat of arms of Sweden.svg|100px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Tre Kronor|cruiser}}\n|Ship displacement={{Convert|7400|LT|t|0}} \n|Ship length= {{Convert|181.96|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam= {{Convert|16.45|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= \n|Ship draft={{Convert|5.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=2 shafts, 90000shp\n|Ship speed= {{Convert|33|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=618\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*''As built'' :\n*7 \u00d7 [[Bofors 152 mm gun]]s\n*20 \u00d7 [[Bofors 40 mm gun]]s\n*9 \u00d7 20 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 torpedo tubes\n*''From 1950'' :\n*7 \u00d7 {{Convert|152|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} guns\n*21 \u00d7 40 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 20 mm guns\n*6 \u00d7 torpedo tubes\n|Ship armor=*{{Convert|70|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n*Deck: {{Convert|30|+|30|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n*Conning tower and turrets: {{Convert|127|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} \n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HSwMS ''Tre Kronor''''' was a [[cruiser]] of the [[Royal Swedish Navy]] built during the [[Second World War]]. \n\n== History ==\nAt the start of the war most of the ships of the Royal Swedish Navy were quite old and the navy was in need of new ships. In 1940 the government decided that three [[cruiser]]s were to be built. A political debate broke out about the cruisers and works did not start until 1943.  The ship was to be built in [[G\u00f6taverken]] in [[Gothenburg]]. Eventually only two of the cruisers were built, and the third cruiser-squadron of the [[Coastal Fleet]] would be led by the modernised AA-cruiser {{HSwMS|Gotland|1933|6}}.\n\nThe turrets used on HSwMS ''Tre Kronor'' were built by [[Bofors]] and were originally ordered by the [[Royal Netherlands Navy|Dutch Navy]] to be fitted on the two \"[[De Zeven Provinci\u00ebn-class cruiser]]s\", but after the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[German occupation of the Netherlands (Reichskommissariat)|occupation of the Netherlands]] the [[Sweden|Swedish]] government was afraid they would be claimed by the Germans so they were confiscated.\n\n''Tre Kronor'' was launched 16 December 1944, commissioned on 25 October 1947, and served until 1 January 1964.\n\n==Captains==\n*1947\u20131948: Erik af Klint\n*1949\u20131951: Erik Friberg\n*1954\u20131954: [[Harry Bong]]\n*1954\u20131955: Magnus Starck\n*1955\u20131956: [[\u00c5ke Lindemalm]]\n*1956\u20131957: Magnus Hammar\n*1957\u20131958: Anders Nilson\n\n== References ==\n\n\n{{Tre Kronor class cruiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tre Kronor}}\n\n[[Category:Tre Kronor-class cruisers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Gothenburg]]\n[[Category:1944 ships]]\n\n\n[[it:Almirante Latorre (CL-04)#Origini]]\n", "name_user": "Saftgurka", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCaptains", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HSwMS_Tre_Kronor"}
